Taylor leads you towards the history section of the library and he pulls out a book titled "Zernia and the known Races" he states that this is the most detailed book they have and states that he has to go back to the counter to help. As he walks away you begin reading about the races of Zernia and learn the many different races.

Rethians: Sentinels of the Highlands

Nestled within the craggy peaks of Nergorumia, the Rethians stand as solitary guardians of their mountainous domain. Despite succumbing to Pozian conquest to the south, these stalwart humans maintain a fierce autonomy, wielding spears and pikes with mastery. Their towering stature, a testament to their highland heritage, belies their prowess in trade, offering bountiful animal goods from wool to leather.

Elladani: Riders of the Northern Winds

Once nomadic wanderers, the Elladani now claim dominion over the northern reaches of Korla. Their mastery of equine warfare, whether as cavalry or charioteers, has struck fear into the hearts of unprepared adversaries for centuries. Among their myriad accomplishments, none shine brighter than the marble statues adorning their settlements, crafted with skill and reverence by Elladani stonemasons sought after by rulers far and wide.

Pozians: Lords of the Seas

Born from the restless waves, the Pozians emerge as adept sailors and cunning pirates, carving their legacy upon the shores of the Nergorumian Kingdom. Once masters of the Karlan-Midrin Isles, their maritime dominion waned amidst the tumult of wars and revolts, relinquishing their overseas holdings. Yet, their seafaring prowess endures, a testament to their indomitable spirit upon the vast expanse of the sea.

Zaxsen: Warriors of the Wilds

In the shadowed depths of northwest Korla, the Zaxsen hold sway, their ferocity matched only by their skill in axe craft. Masters of the forest, they navigate its labyrinthine depths with ease, forging weapons of unparalleled quality and trading them with equal fervor. Though their recklessness in battle oft leads to attrition, the Zaxsen remain a force to be reckoned with, their resolve unyielding as the ancient oaks they call home.

Terathi: Guardians of the Desert Sands

Amidst the unforgiving deserts of southern Korla, the Terathi find solace in their mastery of desert warfare. Mounted upon swift camels, they strike with precision under the burning sun, their navy a formidable bulwark against would-be invaders seeking to plunder the fertile eastern provinces. Through sand and sea, the Terathi endure, their resolve unbroken amidst the arid expanse.

Rui: Keepers of the Waters

Beside the tranquil shores of the great Lake Dourinha, the Rui ply their trade, their livelihood intertwined with the ebb and flow of its waters. Peaceful traders and skilled fishermen, they traverse the watery expanses with ease, their swiftness matched only by their prowess in swamp warfare. Clad in scale armor, they strike with the fury of a tempest, their resilience mirrored in the currents they call home.

Latam: Guardians of the Obsidian Realm

Amidst the shadowed slopes of Mt. Koric, the Latam carve their legacy in obsidian, their weapons honed to a deadly edge. Unlike their peaceful Rui neighbors, the Latam are warriors born, their raids for prisoners a testament to their martial prowess. Light armor adorns their frames, hastening their advance in battle, their resolve unyielding as the mountain peaks from whence they draw their strength.

Gariyar: Riders of the Wyrm

Southward, beyond the main horde, lie the lands of the Gariyar, marked by prophecy and steeped in mystery. Led by the visionary Chief Garit I, they settled the southern reaches of Korla, trading goods akin to their Lus brethren but with a unique twist. Masters of dragon and wyrm riding, they strike fear into the hearts of their foes, their enigmatic presence shrouded in legend and myth.

Lus: Nomads of the Windswept Plains

Across the windswept plains of Korla roam the Lus, kin to the Elladani yet steadfast in their nomadic traditions. Skilled herders and raiders, they traverse the land with ease, their trade in animal products a testament to their resourcefulness. Unlike many, the Lus value skill over lineage, their worth measured by the mastery of their craft rather than the blood that flows within their veins.

